Scenes into which a musical clement entered were of two kinds. They were either (u) declaimed in recitative style, with flute accompaniment, or (b) they were actually sung to set tunes. Both ol these kinds ol soenes were known as cantica The former (u) were composed either in lambio octonarii, or in trochaic or iambic septenarii. 'Phe latter (b) were distinctly lyrical soenes, composed in a variety of metros, including not only the more unusual once, such as the cretic, bacchiac, and trochaic octonarii, but also those mentioned in connection with (a) the merely recited cantica.¹ Livius Andronicus introduced the custom of having these lyrical cantica sung by ayoung slave, who stood near the flute-player, while the actor merely gesticulated in a suitable manner. This singer was probably the cantor, who pronounced the plaudite at the close of the play, and is referred to in the well-known lines of Horace : -

Sl plausoris eges aulaea manentis et usque Sessuri donec cantor ‘Vos plaudite’ dicat. (Ara Poet. 154-155.)2
